{"title_page": "Awdat Asoid", "text_new": "{{cleanup|date=July 2010}}\n\n{{Infobox television\n|show_name          = Asweed's Return\n|image              = Awdat Asoid.jpg\n|caption            = Promotional poster\n|show_name_2 = \u0639\u0648\u062f\u0629 \u0639\u0635\u0648\u064a\u062f\n|runtime            = 40 minutes\n|camera             = [[Multi-camera]]\n|creator            =\n|director           = Adnan Ibrahim\n|starring           = [[Nasir Al-Gasabi]]<br />[[Abdullah Al-Sadhan]]<br />[[Mohammad Al-Ali]]<br />[[Rashid Al Shamrani]]\n|executive_producer = ARA of artistic production\n|co_exec_producer   =\n|asst_producer      =\n|prod_coordinator   =\n|editor             =\n|co-producer        =\n|opentheme          =\n|website            =\n|picture_format     =\n|country            = [[Saudi Arabia]]\n|language           = Arabic\n|network            =\n|first_aired        = 1985\n|last_aired         = 1985\n|num_seasons        = 1\n|num_episodes       = 7\n|list_episodes      =\n}}\n'''''Asweed's Return''''' ({{lang-ar|\u0639\u0648\u062f\u0629 \u0639\u0635\u0648\u064a\u062f}}) is one of the most famous Saudi television series in the [[Arab world]].<ref>\"http://www.alriyadh.com/2006/03/24/article140640.html.\" ''Riyadh Newspaper''.2006/03/24.</ref> This series was produced in 1985,<ref>\"http://www.alriyadh.com/2009/01/02/article399477.html.\" ''Riyadh Newspaper''.2009/01/02.</ref> by ARA of artistic production, directed  by Adnan Ibrahim (Iraqi director) and authored by Mohammed Al-Tawayan, both the participated from [[Saudi Arabia]] and [[Syria]]. Although the series is short, it was thoroughly enjoyed by its viewers.\n\n==Synopsis==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|The story of the show is about a Bedouin tribe and its sheikh (Abo Asweed), who is bedridden, and he mutters about something in a box, and he wants to give the box to a certain person. Shortly after, all the tribesmen is on the pursuit of this box.\n|}\n\n==Starring==\n* Mohammed Al-Tawayan\n*[[Mohammad Al-Ali]]\n*[[Muna Wassef]]\n*[[Rashid Al Shamrani]]\n*[[Nasir Al-Gasabi]]\n* [[Abdullah Al-Sadhan]]\n* Mohammed Al-Kanhal\n* Amanah Wali\n* Khalid Al-Salm\n* Salwa Noor al-Din\n* Khaled Sami\n\n==Direction==\n* Adnan ibrahim\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1985 Saudi Arabian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1985 Saudi Arabian television series endings]]\n[[Category:1980s Saudi Arabian television series]]\n[[Category:Media in Saudi Arabia]]\n", "text_old": "{{cleanup|date=July 2010}}\n\n{{Infobox television\n|show_name          = Asweed's Return\n|image              = Awdat Asoid.jpg\n|caption            = Promotional poster\n|show_name_2 = \u0639\u0648\u062f\u0629 \u0639\u0635\u0648\u064a\u062f\n|runtime            = 40 minutes\n|camera             = [[Multi-camera]]\n|creator            =\n|director           = Adnan Ibrahim\n|starring           = [[Nasir Al-Gasabi]]<br />[[Abdullah Al-Sadhan]]<br />[[Mohammad Al-Ali]]<br />[[Rashid Al Shamrani]]\n|executive_producer = ARA of artistic production\n|co_exec_producer   =\n|asst_producer      =\n|prod_coordinator   =\n|editor             =\n|co-producer        =\n|opentheme          =\n|website            =\n|picture_format     =\n|country            = [[Saudi Arabia]]\n|language           = Arabic\n|network            =\n|first_aired        = 1985\n|last_aired         = 1985\n|num_seasons        = 1\n|num_episodes       = 7\n|list_episodes      =\n}}\n'''''Asweed's Return''''' ({{lang-ar|\u0639\u0648\u062f\u0629 \u0639\u0635\u0648\u064a\u062f}}) is one of the most famous Saudi television series in the [[Arab world]].<ref>\"http://www.alriyadh.com/2006/03/24/article140640.html.\" ''Riyadh Newspaper''.2006/03/24.</ref> This series was produced in 1985,<ref>\"http://www.alriyadh.com/2009/01/02/article399477.html.\" ''Riyadh Newspaper''.2009/01/02.</ref> by ARA of artistic production, directed  by Adnan Ibrahim (Iraqi director) and authored by Mohammed Al-Tawayan, both the participated from [[Saudi Arabia]] and [[Syria]]. Although the series is short, it was thoroughly enjoyed by its viewers.\n\n==Synopsis==\nThe story of this series is about a Bedouin tribe, the Sheikh of this tribe (Abo Asweed) is Bedridden,\nand close to death, his cousin (Abo Kazan) was trying to in pursuit of gold. Shortly after, all the tribesmen was also trying to capture the gold.\n\n==Starring==\n* Mohammed Al-Tawayan\n*[[Mohammad Al-Ali]]\n*[[Muna Wassef]]\n*[[Rashid Al Shamrani]]\n*[[Nasir Al-Gasabi]]\n* [[Abdullah Al-Sadhan]]\n* Mohammed Al-Kanhal\n* Amanah Wali\n* Khalid Al-Salm\n* Salwa Noor al-Din\n* Khaled Sami\n\n==Direction==\n* Adnan ibrahim\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1985 Saudi Arabian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1985 Saudi Arabian television series endings]]\n[[Category:1980s Saudi Arabian television series]]\n[[Category:Media in Saudi Arabia]]\n", "name_user": "AbdullahTalal", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSynopsis", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Awdat_Asoid"}
{"title_page": "Mudbound (film)", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Mudbound\n| image          = Mudbound (film).png\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Promotional release poster\n| director       = [[Dee Rees]]\n| producer       = {{ubl|Carl Effenson|Sally Jo Effenson|[[Cassian Elwes]]|Charles King|Christopher Lemole|Kim Roth|Tim Zajaros}}\n| screenplay     = {{ubl|Dee Rees|[[Virgil Williams]]}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Mudbound (novel)|Mudbound]]''|[[Hillary Jordan]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Carey Mulligan]]\n* [[Jason Clarke]]\n* [[Jason Mitchell]]\n* [[Mary J. Blige]]\n* [[Rob Morgan (actor)|Rob Morgan]]\n* [[Jonathan Banks]]\n* [[Garrett Hedlund]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Tamar-kali]]\n| cinematography = [[Rachel Morrison]]\n| editing        = Mako Kamitsuna\n| released       = {{Film date|2017|01|21|[[2017 Sundance Film Festival|Sundance]]|2017|11|17|United States}}\n| studio         = {{ubl|Elevated Films|Joule Films}}\n| distributor    = [[Netflix]]\n| country        = United States\n| runtime        = 134 minutes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/mudbound-2017-0|title = Mudbound|website = [[British Board of Film Classification]]|accessdate = November 17, 2017}}</ref>\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $10 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/markets-festivals/netflix-buys-sundance-drama-mudbound-for-12-5-million-1201972765/|title=Netflix Buys Sundance Drama 'Mudbound' for $12.5 Million|website=Variety|date=January 29, 2017|accessdate=October 26, 2017}}</ref>\n| gross          = $117,344<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=mudbound.htm|title=Mudbound (2017)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Mudbound''''' is a 2017 American [[historical drama]] film directed by [[Dee Rees]] and written by Rees and [[Virgil Williams]], based on the novel [[Mudbound (novel)|of the same name]] by [[Hillary Jordan]]. It stars [[Carey Mulligan]], [[Garrett Hedlund]], [[Jason Clarke]], [[Jason Mitchell]], [[Jonathan Banks]], and [[Mary J. Blige]]. The film depicts two [[World War II]] veterans \u2013 one white, one black \u2013 who return to rural [[Mississippi]] each to address racism and [[PTSD]] in his own way. The film premiered at the [[2017 Sundance Film Festival]] on January 21, 2017,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Patten|first1=Dominic|url=http://deadline.com/2016/12/sundance-2017-premieres-midnight-special-events-robert-redford-rashida-jones-1201864406/|title=Sundance 2017: Robert Redford, New Rashida Jones Netflix Series, 'Rebel In The Rye' & More On Premiere, Docu, Midnight & Kids Slates|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=December 5, 2016}}</ref> and was released on [[Netflix]] and in [[limited release]] on November 17, 2017.\n\nCritics praised its screenplay, direction, and the cast's performances (particularly those of Mitchell and Blige)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/sundance-mudbound-premieres-to-rapturous-standing-ovation-and-oscar-buzz-1201966318/|title=Sundance: 'Mudbound' Premieres to Rapturous Standing Ovation and Oscar Buzz|website=Variety|date=January 21, 2017|accessdate=October 26, 2017}}</ref>  and at the [[75th Golden Globe Awards]] received nominations for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Supporting Actress]] (Blige) and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] (\"Mighty River\").<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/golden-globe-nominations-2018-nominees-full-list-1202634435/|title=Golden Globe Nominations: Complete List|work=Variety|date=December 11, 2017|accessdate=December 11, 2017|first=Rebecca|last=Rubin}}</ref> At the [[90th Academy Awards]], the film earned four nominations: [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] and [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for Blige, [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]], and [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]], the latter of which made [[Rachel Morrison]] the first woman ever nominated in the category. Blige became the first person to ever be nominated for an acting and song award during the same year.\n\n== Plot ==\nIn Mississippi delta farm country, Henry McAllan and his younger brother Jamie dig a grave and struggle to lower their deceased Pappy's coffin into it. When the Jacksons, a black sharecropper family, pass by in a wagon, Henry asks the father, Hap, for help. Henry seems uncomfortable asking; Hap hesitates to reply.\n\nThe film goes back to 1939, when Henry buys a farm outside the fictional town of Marietta, Mississippi, in the [[Mississippi Delta]], and moves there with his wife Laura, with whom he shares a passionless marriage, their daughters, and the virulently racist Pappy. The Jackson family, led by tenant farmer Hap and his wife Florence, work the farm's cotton field and dream of owning their own land one day.\n\nAs World War II begins, Jamie and the Jacksons' eldest son, Ronsel, join the Air Force and Army, respectively. Jamie flys bombers and Ronsel commands tanks and falls in love with a white German woman. Both experience severe combat trauma. \n\nMeanwhile, back in Mississippi both families live in poverty, at the edge of disaster. The families support each other out of necessity. The Jacksons' mule has to be put down. Henry offers to share his mule, but exacts half of the Jackson's crop in payment; the Jacksons have no choice but to accept. Florence helps Laura when Laura and Henry's two small daughters are ill with whooping cough, and Laura offers Florence work helping care for her daughters. Hap, who serves as the preacher for the local black community, falls while helping to build a small church, breaking a leg and rendering him unable to work. Laura sneaks money from her husband's safe so Hap can be treated by a doctor.\n\nWhen the war ends, Ronsel and Jamie return home and realize that they've changed, but the local society hasn't. Jamie becomes an alcoholic and suffers from PTSD. Ronsel, accustomed to the relative lack of racism among Europeans, struggles with racism back home. They become aware of each others' difficulties and bond over their war experiences. Ronsel asks why Jamie treats him with respect; Jamie recounts that on a bomber flight, a black fighter pilot saved his life. Jamie's drunkenness gets worse and he wakes up from a nightmare  with the car partially submerged in a lake. Henry leaves on a trip and tells Jamie to leave the farm before he returns.\n\nRonsel receives a letter from the German woman with whom he'd been romantically involved during the war. He learns that they had a child together and she wants Ronsel to join them. He shares this with Jamie while riding together in the McAllans' truck. Their truck passes Pappy and Ronsel must hide. Pappy confronts Jamie about seeing him with Rondel. He yells at Jamie for his drunken behavior and sneers at Laura, claiming she has feelings for Jamie. Later, Ronsel realizes that he lost the letter and photo and runs out to look for it. Pappy finds the letter and photo in the truck. Laura confronts Jamie as he packs to leave, and they make love. \n\nAs Ronsel searches for his letter, he is ambushed by Pappy and members of the Ku Klux Klan and beaten. Pappy brings Jamie to a barn where the Klan is preparing to kill Ronsel for fathering a child with a white woman. Jamie points a gun at his father in an effort to save his friend, and is beaten by members of the Klan. As Jamie is restrained and in pain, he is told to choose Ronsel's punishment for his crime -- to lose his eyes, tongue or testicles -- or watch Ronsel be put to death. Through the pain, Jamie whispers \"tongue\" and Ronsel's tongue is cut out. Ronsel is left bound and wounded for his family to find. \n\nLater that night, Jamie wakes Pappy. Pappy had previously belittled Jamie's war awards because he hadn't had to look in the eyes of the people he killed. Jamie looks Pappy in the eye and smothers him with a pillow.\n\nThe film returns to the opening scene. The Jacksons appear to be leaving with their meager belongings in the wagon. Hap accedes to Henry's request to help with the coffin and says a prayer over the grave. In a rebuke to Pappy, Hap recites from the Book of Job, verses 14:2-12. As Henry begins to bury his father, Jamie walks away. He approaches the Jacksons' wagon and gives the German woman's envelope to Florence, asking her to give it to Ronsel if she should see him. \n\nMuch later, Jamie moves to the city. Ronsel makes his way back to Europe and reunites with the German woman and his son.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{div col}}\n<!--- Per end credits --->\n* [[Carey Mulligan]] as Laura McAllan (n\u00e9e Chappell)\n* [[Jason Clarke]] as Henry McAllan\n* [[Mary J. Blige]] as Florence Jackson\n* [[Rob Morgan (actor)|Rob Morgan]] as Hap Jackson\n* [[Jason Mitchell]] as Ronsel Jackson\n* [[Garrett Hedlund]] as Jamie McAllan\n* [[Jonathan Banks]] as Pappy McAllan\n* Frankie Smith as Marlon Jackson\n* Kennedy Derosin as Lilly May Jackson\n* Elizabeth Windley as Amanda Leigh McAllan\n* Piper Blaire as Isabelle McAllan\n* Jason Kirkpatrick as Orris Stokes\n* Kerry Cahill as Rose Tricklebank\n* Oyeleke Oluwafolakanmi as Cleve\n* [[Kelvin Harrison Jr.]] as Weeks\n* Lucy Faust as Vera Atwood\n* [[Dylan Arnold]] as Carl Atwood\n* Samantha H\u00f6efer as Resl\n* Geraldine Singer as Mrs. Chappell\n* Henry Frost as Teddy Chappell\n* Claudio Laniado as Dr. Pearlman\n* Charley Vance as Sheriff Thacker\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Production ==\nDevelopment on the film was announced on March 21, 2016, with [[Dee Rees]] engaged as director and [[Carey Mulligan]], [[Garrett Hedlund]], [[Jason Clarke]] and [[Jason Mitchell]] cast in roles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/carey-mulligan-jason-clarke-garrett-hedlund-ww2-movie-mud-bound-1201729904/|title=Garrett Hedlund, Carey Mulligan, Jason Clarke and Jason Mitchell to Star in 'Mudbound' (EXCLUSIVE)|first=Justin|last=Kroll|date=March 21, 2016|website=Variety.com|access-date=November 21, 2017}}</ref> On May 25, [[Mary J. Blige]] was added to the cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/05/mary-j-blige-cast-mudbound-jason-mitchell-macro-world-war-2-1201762703/|title=Mary J. Blige Joins Cast of 'Mudbound' With Jason Mitchell, Jason Clarke, Garrett Hedlund & Carey Mulligan|first=Ali|last=Jaafar|date=May 25, 2016|website=Deadline.com|access-date=November 21, 2017}}</ref> On May 31, [[Jonathan Banks]] and Rob Morgan were cast, and filming began in [[New Orleans, Louisiana]] and post-production started in the United Kingdom by July 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/05/melissa-mccarthy-can-you-ever-forgive-me-movie-lee-israel-1201764700/|title='Mudbound' Cast Set; XLrator-IndustryWorks Pact For Action Thrillers; Melissa McCarthy To Star In 'Can You Ever Forgive Me?' \u2013 Film Briefs|first=Patrick|last=Hipes|date=May 31, 2016|website=Deadline.com|access-date=November 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Cinematography ==\nDee Rees asked Rachel Morrison to focus on \"the idea of the American dream vs. the American reality\", so Rachel turned to books by Farm Security Administration photographers for reference points regarding color and composition, in particular [[Dorothea Lange]], [[Arthur Rothstein]], [[Ben Shahn]] and [[Walker Evans]]. Another primary source for her was a [[Gordon Parks]] essay in [[Life (magazine)|''Life'' magazine]] in the 1950s called \"A Segregation Story\" \u2013 regarding color that \"felt [[Historical period drama|period]], but it didn't feel washed-out\".<ref name=Buder>{{cite web| last1=Buder |first1=Emily |title= How ''Mudbound'' DP Rachel Morrison Created 'Natural Light' By Lighting Heavily |url= https://nofilmschool.com/2017/11/mudbound-rachel-morrison-cinematographer-dp-interview |work=No Film School |date=December 1, 2017 |access-date=February 19, 2018}}</ref> Rachel's term for the goal they tried to achieve is \"subjective naturalism\", which she describes as first of all, real; and then potentially dramatized with light at main plot points \u2013 but remaining real throughout.<ref name=Buder /> Through that reality, the focus was on the elements in the picture and not the period itself: \"The period wasn't a character in this film. The mud was a character, the weather was a character, the house was a character ... we were trying to make more of a commentary about just how tough times were through experiences.\"<ref name=Buder /> [[A. O. Scott]] in the ''[[New York Times]]'' on the result: \"Rachel ... brings the soil, the flora and the weather to life in a way that emphasizes the archaic, elemental power of the story.\" <ref name=Scott>{{cite web| last=Scott |first=A. O. |author-link=A. O. Scott | title=Review: ''Mudbound'' Is a Racial Epic Tuned to Black Lives, and White Guilt |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/16/movies/mudbound-review-dee-rees.html?referrer=google_kp |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 16, 2017 |access-date=February 19, 2018| page=}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nFollowing its [[2017 Sundance Film Festival]] premiere, ''Mudbound'' had distribution offers from [[A24 (company)|A24]] and [[Annapurna Pictures]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tracking-board.com/current-awards-season-affecting-mudbound-bidding-war-which-includes-a24-annapurna-exclusive/|title=Current Awards Season Affecting \"Mudbound\" Bidding War, Which Includes A24, Annapurna (Exclusive)|date=January 25, 2017|accessdate=January 26, 2017}}</ref> On January 29, 2017, [[Netflix]] acquired distribution rights to the film.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fleming Jr.|first1=Mike|title=Netflix Paying $12.5M For Dee Rees-Directed 'Mudbound' \u2013 Sundance|url=http://deadline.com/2017/01/mudbound-netflix-12-5-million-dollars-dee-reese-sundance-film-festival-carey-mulligan-jason-clarke-mary-j-blige-garrett-hedlund-1201897022/|date=January 29, 2017|work=Deadline}}</ref> The film premiered on the streaming platform, as well as began a one week theatrical release in [[New York City]] and [[Los Angeles]], on November 17, 2017.\n\n=== Critical response ===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 97% based on 185 reviews, with an average rating of 8.22/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''Mudbound'' offers a well-acted, finely detailed snapshot of American history whose scenes of rural class struggle resonate far beyond their period setting.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Mudbound (2017)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/mudbound/|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|accessdate= August 23, 2019 }}</ref> On [[Metacritic]] the film has a weighted average score of 85 out of 100, based on 44 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/mudbound |title=Mudbound Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=December 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Richard Roeper]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film 3.5 out of 4 stars, praising the cast and direction.<ref>{{cite news |last=Roeper |first=Richard |author-link= Richard Roeper |date=November 16, 2017 |title=Signs of hope can be a beautiful thrill in searing world of 'Mudbound' |url= https://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment/signs-of-hope-can-be-a-beautiful-thrill-in-searing-world-of-mudbound/ |website=[[Chicago Sun Times]] |accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', [[Peter Travers]] also gave the film 3.5 out of 4 stars, praising Blige's performance and Rees' direction, saying: \"The director and her cinematographer [[Rachel Morrison]] do wonders with the elements that batter the people of every race and social class in the Delta. But it's the storm raging inside these characters that rivets our attention and makes ''Mudbound'' a film that grabs you and won't let go.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Travers |first=Peter |author-link= Peter Travers|title='Mudbound' Review: Epic Drama on Poverty, Race and Family Is 'Stunning Achievement'|url= https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/peter-travers-epic-drama-mudbound-is-a-stunning-achievement-w511646|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=November 27, 2017|accessdate=November 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Date of ceremony\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Recipient(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n| [[AACTA Awards|AACTA International Awards]]\n| [[7th AACTA International Awards|January 6, 2018]]\n| [[AACTA International Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]\n| [[Mary J. Blige]]\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/three-billboards-australian-academy-international-awards-1202655103/|title='Three Billboards' Wins Best Film at Australian Academy International Awards|last=McNary|first=Dave|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=January 5, 2018|accessdate=January 6, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106185639/http://variety.com/2018/film/news/three-billboards-australian-academy-international-awards-1202655103/|archivedate=January 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[AARP|AARP's Movies for Grownups Awards]]\n| February 5, 2018\n| Best Ensemble\n| The cast of ''Mudbound''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/aarps-movies-grownups-awards-2018-post-leads-nominees-1075285/item/ |title=AARP's Movies for Grownups Awards: 'The Post' Leads Nominees |last=Lee |first=Ashley |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=January 17, 2018|accessdate=January 17, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[Academy Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[90th Academy Awards|March 4, 2018]]\n| [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]\n| Mary J. Blige\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/list-2018-oscar-nominations-1202668757/|title=Oscar Nominations 2018: The Complete List|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=January 23, 2018 |accessdate=January 24, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]]\n| [[Dee Rees]] and [[Virgil Williams]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]]\n| \"[[Mighty River (song)|Mighty River]]\" \u2013 Mary J. Blige, [[Raphael Saadiq]] and [[Taura Stinson]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]\n| [[Rachel Morrison]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"| [[Alliance of Women Film Journalists]]\n| rowspan=\"5\"| January 9, 2018\n| Best Adapted Screenplay\n| Dee Rees and Virgil Williams\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://awfj.org/eda-awards-2/2017-awfj-eda-award-nominees/|title=2017 AWFJ EDA Award Nominees|publisher=[[Alliance of Women Film Journalists]]|date=January 3, 2018|accessdate=January 3, 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20180103084642/http://awfj.org/eda-awards-2/2017-awfj-eda-award-nominees/|archivedate=January 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Actress in a Supporting Role\n| Mary J. Blige\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Ensemble Cast \u2013 Casting Director\n| Billy Hopkins and Ashley Ingram\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Best Woman Director\n| Dee Rees\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Woman Screenwriter\n| Dee Rees and Virgil Williams\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[American Society of Cinematographers]]\n| [[2017 American Society of Cinematographers Awards|February 17, 2018]]\n| [[American Society of Cinematographers Award for Outstanding Achievement in Cinematography in Theatrical Releases|Outstanding Achievement in Cinematography in Theatrical Releases]]\n| Rachel Morrison\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref name=\"RMASC18\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/mudbound-gives-american-society-cinematographers-first-ever-female-film-nominee/ |title='Mudbound' Gives American Society of Cinematographers Its First-Ever Female Film Nominee |last=Pond |first=Steve |date=January 9, 2018 |website=Variety |access-date=January 10, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[Austin Film Critics Association]]\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[Austin Film Critics Association Awards 2017|January 8, 2018]]\n| Best Supporting Actress\n| Mary J. Blige\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nextbestpicture.com/latest/the-2017-austin-film-critics-association-afca-nominations| title=The 2017 Austin Film Critics Association (AFCA) Nominations| last=Neglia| first=Matt| date=December 30, 2017| work=nextbestpicture.com| accessdate=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Adapted Screenplay\n| Dee Rees and Virgil Williams\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Cinematography\n| Rachel Morrison\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\"| [[Black Reel Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"8\"| [[Black Reel Awards of 2018|February 22, 2018]]\n| [[Black Reel Award for Outstanding Film|Outstanding Film]]\n| ''Mudbound''\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>[http://blackreelawards.com/get-out-dominate-the-black-reel-awards/ Get Out Dominates the Black Reel Awards] Black Reel Awards. 13 December 2017.</ref><ref>[http://blackreelawards.com/get-out-sinks-the-competition-at-the-black-reel-awards/ Get Out \u201cSinks\u201d the Competition at The Black Reel Awards] Black Reel Awards. 23 February 2018.</ref>\n|-\n| [[Black Reel Award for Outstanding Director|Outstanding Director]]\n| Dee Rees\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Black Reel Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor|Outstanding Supporting Actor]]\n| [[Jason Mitchell]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Black Reel Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress|Outstanding Supporting Actress]]\n| Mary J. Blige\n| {{